I just realized I'm not being clear about my question.  This code looks like it gets around the operator not having a filesystem store built by building its own (substituting the node_staging_uri for the filesystem_store_dir).  The bug said that we'd have to mention in docs that operators need to have a filesystem store either in 'enabled_backends' or in 'stores' -- is that still the case, or does this patch make that unnecessary?

Patch Set 2:

Brian,

I am sorry for the confusion, actually I have worked on it few months before. Actually as pointed out on the bug, the issue is fixed only when multiple backend is not enabled. If multiple backend is not enabled and 'file' store is not defined in 'stores' config option then data remains in staging area. With this patch I am loading the file store explicitly while deleting the data from the staging area. I haven't changed anything for multiple_backend is because of our 'rethinking file system access spec' and still multiple backend is experimental as well.

As pointed out in the bug we have two options,
1. Get this patch in and fix this problem for single store deployment
2. Document that to use image import we need to have 'file' store in 'stores' option for single store deployment and at-least one 'file' store in case of multiple store deployment (like enabled_backends = 'file1':'file',....)

Patch Set 2:

I just spent some time looking at this more closely.  What was worrying me was that the delete worked fine as long as the operator had a filesystem store configured, but the import workflow shouldn't be using *that* store, so what's the deal?  

Looking at the import workflow:

(1) for the /stage call, the api code builds a file store (using node_staging_uri to get the value for filesystem_store_datadir) and puts the image in there.  This store object ceases to exist when the /stage call is completed.  So this use of the store has nothing to do with the operator's "real" filesystem store.

(2) for the /import call, the api code creates an api_image_import task.

(2a) For storing the staged data into a real backend, the task does not actually use the filesystem store, but rather uses glance.common.scripts.image_import.main.set_image_data, passing it the file_path (which is actually a uri) to the location where the data is located in the staging area.  So again, this can't affect the operator's "real" filesystem store.  (But this will have to be changed eventually.)

(2b) For deleting the staged data, the task uses _DeleteFromFS, which calls glance_store.backend.delete_from_backend(file_path), which reads the scheme from the file_path to get a store and then calls store.delete() on that store--which should be the operator's "real" filesystem store!

The filed bug is that if 'file' isn't defined in the api-conf 'stores', this deletion fails.
The solution in this patch is to not use delete_from_backend, but instead build a file store and then call .delete() directly on it.  (This way we don't rely on getting a store by searching through the registered schemes.)

This is nice, because this store that we just built is *not* the same as the operator's "real" filesystem store.

Q: why was this working earlier, when it was using the *wrong* filesystem store?
A: glance_store._drivers.filesystem.Store.delete() just calls os.unlink() on the file path for a location it's handed -- it does not check to see if the location is in any way related to its filesystem_data_dir (i.e., it will delete stuff that it doesn't "own").  NOTE: This seems unsafe.

Conceptually, then, this patch does seem to work for the non-multiple-backend case, it will allow image import to work without requiring an operator to have a filesystem store configured.

OK, so the multi-backend case.  We don't want the operator to configure a filesystem store in enabled_backends, because that will make it available to end users.

I notice that for the /stage call, the api code doesn't pay any attention to enabled_backends.

So why not just use the same strategy as for the non-multi-backend situation?
In other words, just unconditonally use the code at lines 131-136, and don't bother to check enabled_backends at all.

This is going to have to be refactored for Train anyway (see 2a, above); at least this will allow operators to use both  multiple backends AND image import in Stein.
